Implement the following algorithm (from 'mastering algorithms in Perl, pg 307):
bfs ( graph G, Node u)
create a queue with u as the initial node
mark Node u as seen
while there are vertices in the queue
do
dequeue vertex v
mark v as seen
enqueue unseen neighboring vertices of v
done

Implement the following algorithm (from 'mastering algorithms in Perl, pg 302):
dfs ( graph G, Node u)
mark Node u as seen
for every unseen neighboring Node of u called v
do
dfs v
done
We set the root Node to be a node from the unseenNodes Vector with the smallest number of inEdges (as long as the number of outEdges is greater than zero).
This traversal is the same as the bfs except that we don't add a given node to the queue until all inEdges of that node connect to nodes that have been included in the list already

Title: ViewDefinition

Description: This class encapsulates the design of a view within the system. A view is a multi-object entity that has an individual identity as a standalone thing. The view encapsulates data from all constituitive tables and objects to represent that.

Copyright: Copyright (c) 2004

Company: University of Southern California

@author Gully APC Burns @version 1.28
The views type, could take any one value from DATA, SYSTEM, LOOKUP, LINK, COLLECTION or EXTERNAL (see below for explanation)
A view of type DATA is a standard data view. This appears in the viewDefinitionGraph and may be manipulated directly by users.

A view of type SYSTEM is a view generated and used by the system to keep track of user information and other details. These views are not directly accessible to users but are manipulated by the application.
A view of type LOOKUP is typically a lightweight view that permits DATA views to be retrieved by indexString. This permits lightweight controls (such as lookup boxes) to access them

A view of type LINK has a set structure and is used to query the knowledge base for links between DATA views. The primary primitive of this view is always based around the the ViewLinkTable of the system. These views may also contain quite complex information.

A view of type COLLECTION is treated by the system like a DATA view in every way, except that it typically contains DATA views. This is a semantic difference and may be represented explicitly in the system at a future time.
A view of type EXTERNAL is supplied by an external source or a reference ontology. It is not usually editable.

Disconnected - None of the pvs in $fromView has any relationship with any of the pvs in $toView
Connected - The primary primitive of $fromView has a one-way connection with the primary primitive of $toView - Note that lookup Views may not be involved in 'Connected' View Links
Interconnected - The primary primitive of $fromView has a reciprocal connection with the primary primitive of $toView
Superset - The pvs of $fromView have a superset or identical relationship with all of the pvs of $toView
Subset - All of the pvs of $fromView have a subset or identical relationship with all of the pvs of $fromView
Overlap - Some of the pvs of $fromView have a superset or identical relationship with all of the pvs of $toView
